2. Plautus. His great successor Titus Maca'us Plautus (T. Maccius, not M. Accius, was proved to be his name by Ritschl from the Ambrosian MS.) devoted his entire attention to Comedy. Of Plautus' life but little is known. He was born at Sarsina-now Sassina-a municipium in Umbria, and so like most great Roman writers, Cicero, Vergil, Horace, Livy, Tacitus, Catullus, Propertius, Terence, Pliny, Martial, &c.‚ was a provincial by birth. He came to Rome as a boy, was known there as Plautus, a name according to Festus (p. 239 M.) derived from a peculiarity of the feet, as the Umbrians called a flat-footed man Plotus or Plautus. Thus Plautus is one of the many nick-names that became hereditary cognomina, as Scaevola, Cursor, &c He found employment as an assistant to the stage-carpenters and scene-painters (artefices scenici), made some money, which he lost in foreign trade, returned poor to Rome and hired himself to a miller (pistor), and in this position wrote his first three pieces for the stage. lf we allow time for these experiences we cannot make him less than 30 when he began to write. As further he was a contemporary, like Naevius, of the two Scipios, and i's regularly coupled with them and NaeviuS, we must assume that he began to write agood many years before their death 212. Brut. 72), and that he wrote the Pseudolus and T ruculentus as senex (Cic. Cato M. 50). The Pseudolus belongs apparently to 191 lae, and Plautus to be called senex must then have been not less than 60years of age. He died (Cic. Brut. 60) 184 B.c.
